 checkpoint would have added it. A subsequent cherry-pick that modifies it would be modifying a path that was just added by an earlier cherry-pick. \\n\\nThis is safe — we're only touching our own data.\\n\\n**Deletions**: The risky part is when we delete a path that existed in the local parent. On the remote tip after cherry-picking, that path could either be something we added earlier (safe to delete) or something that already existed on remote (dangerous — we'd be deleting their data). But this second case can't actually happen because the path was part of the local branch's data, which uses local checkpoint IDs that don't exist on remote.\\n\\nThe shard structure uses the checkpoint ID to create unique directories, so even if two IDs happen to share the same first two characters, the full path would still differ. Non-sharded paths like `metadata.json` at the root are only in test setups, not production. IDs are globally unique, so their sharded paths never overlap between local and remote checkpoints. Deletions are safe because they either remove local additions, are no-ops on missing keys, or can't accidentally target remote data due to this namespace separation.\\n\\nActually, looking at how the metadata branch works in practice, deletions shouldn't occur at all since the system is append-only — the delete logic is just a defensive measure that never gets exercised.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":142,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":135313,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":142},\"output_tokens\":14,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYXXhGtn616VYtmPPXw2R\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"a60e0131-1d35-4407-bbe1-09b688db898a\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-26T23:15:02.361Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"a60e0131-1d35-4407-bbe1-09b688db898a\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"ex