e and confusing -- if the write fails for any other reason (e.g., disk full, permissions), the test would silently create the directory and retry instead of failing.\\n    18→\\n    19→   ```go\\n    20→   if err := os.WriteFile(filepath.Join(dir1, \\\"1\\\", \\\"metadata.json\\\"),\\n    21→       []byte(`{\\\"session_id\\\":\\\"second-session\\\"}`), 0o644); err != nil {\\n    22→       if err := os.MkdirAll(filepath.Join(dir1, \\\"1\\\"), 0o755); err != nil {\\n    23→           t.Fatalf(\\\"failed to create dir: %v\\\", err)\\n    24→       }\\n    25→       if err := os.WriteFile(filepath.Join(dir1, \\\"1\\\", \\\"metadata.json\\\"),\\n    26→           []byte(`{\\\"session_id\\\":\\\"second-session\\\"}`), 0o644); err != nil {\\n    27→           t.Fatalf(\\\"failed to write: %v\\\", err)\\n    28→       }\\n    29→   }\\n    30→   ```\\n    31→\\n    32→   **Suggested fix:** Create the directory first unconditionally, then write the file:\\n    33→   ```go\\n    34→   if err := os.MkdirAll(filepath.Join(dir1, \\\"1\\\"), 0o755); err != nil {\\n    35→       t.Fatalf(\\\"failed to create dir: %v\\\", err)\\n    36→   }\\n    37→   if err := os.WriteFile(filepath.Join(dir1, \\\"1\\\", \\\"metadata.json\\\"),\\n    38→       []byte(`{\\\"session_id\\\":\\\"second-session\\\"}`), 0o644); err != nil {\\n    39→       t.Fatalf(\\\"failed to write: %v\\\", err)\\n    40→   }\\n    41→   ```\\n    42→\\n    43→2. **[common.go:48-59] `sync.Once` global state is not resettable for testing**\\n    44→\\n    45→   The `reconcileOnce` / `reconcileResult` globals use `sync.Once` which means reconciliation runs exactly once per process. This is correct for production, but it creates implicit test ordering dependencies. If any test (or future test) calls `EnsureMetadataReconciled`, the cached result will persist for all subsequent tests in the same `go test` process.\\n    46→\\n    47→   Currently no tests call `EnsureMetadataReconciled` directly, and the reconcile tests call `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch` directly (which is good). But the `getCheckpointStore()` method in `manual_commit.go:55` calls `EnsureMetadataReconciled`, and `ListCheckpoints` in `common.go:135` also calls it. If any integration test triggers these paths, a stale cached error (or a stale nil from a test repo) will leak.\\n    48→\\n    49→   The pattern used elsewhere in this codebase (e.g., `resetProtectedDirsForTest` in `common_test.go:851-854`) is to provide a test-only reset function.\\n    50→\\n    51→   **Suggested fix:** Add a reset function for tests:\\n    52→   ```go\\n    53→   // resetReconcileOnceForTest resets the reconciliation gate for test isolation.\\n    54→   //\\n    55→   //nolint:unused // test utility\\n    56→   func resetReconcileOnceForTest() {\\n    57→       reconcileOnce = sync.Once{}\\n    58→       reconcileResult = nil\\n    59→   }\\n    60→   ```\\n    61→\\n    62→   This is not yet causing failures, but it is a latent correctness issue.\\n    63→\\n    64→### Important (Should Fix)\\n    65→\\n    66→3. **[metadata_reconcile.go:83-91] Silent `continue` on tree error swallows potential real errors**\\n    67→\\n    68→   When filtering empty-tree commits, the code silently skips any commit where `c.Tree()` fails:\\n    69→   ```go\\n    70→   tree, treeErr := c.Tree()\\n    71→   if treeErr != nil {\\n    72→       continue\\n    73→   }\\n    74→   ```\\n    75→   If the tree object is genuinely corrupted or missing (as opposed to empty), this silently drops a data commit. This should at least log a warning. In the normal case (the empty-orphan bug), `c.Tree()` will succeed and return an empty tree -- there is no reason for `Tree()` to fail on a valid commit.\\n    76→\\n    77→   **Suggested fix:** Return an error or at minimum log a warning when `Tree()` fails on a commit that does exist:\\n    78→   ```go\\n    79→   tree, treeErr := c.Tree()\\n    80→   if treeErr != nil {\\n    81→       fmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \\\"[entire] Warning: skipping commit %s with unreadable tree: %v\\\\n\\\", c.Hash.String()[:7], treeErr)\\n    82→       continue\\n    83→   }\\n    84→   ```\\n    85→\\n    86→4. **[metadata_reconcile.go:194] Best-effort `FlattenTree` on parent silently ignores errors**\\n    87→\\n    88→   ```go\\n    89→   _ = checkpoint.FlattenTree(repo, parentTree, \\\"\\\", parentEntries) //nolint:errcheck // best effort\\n    90→   ```\\n    91→   If `FlattenTree` fails on the parent tree, `parentEntries` will be partially populated. The delta computation will then treat any entries that were *not* read as \\\"deleted\\\" in the parent, and any entries that *were* in the commit will be treated as \\\"new.\\\" This could result in an incomplete or incorrect delta being cherry-picked. Since this is a repair operation for user data, correctness should take priority over resilience.\\n    92→\\n    93→   **Suggested fix:** Propagate the error:\\n    94→   ```go\\n    95→   if err := checkpoint.FlattenTree(repo, parentTree, \\\"\\\", parentEntries); err != nil {\\n    96→       return plumbing.ZeroHash, fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to flatten parent tree for commit %s: %w\\\", commit.Hash, err)\\n    97→   }\\n    98→   ```\\n    99→\\n   100→5. **[metadata_reconcile.go:144-167] `collectCommitChain` silently stops at MaxCommitTraversalDepth without warning**\\n   101→\\n   102→   If the local metadata branch has more than 1000 commits (unlikely but possible for heavy users), `collectCommitChain` silently truncates the chain. The cherry-pick would then only replay the most recent 1000 commits, losing older data.\\n   103→\\n   104→   The `for range MaxCommitTraversalDepth` loop exits silently when the limit is reached without reaching the root commit. The caller has no way to know data was truncated.\\n   105→\\n   106→   **Suggested fix:** Either return an error when the depth limit is hit without reaching a root commit, or log a warning:\\n   107→   ```go\\n   108→   for i := range MaxCommitTraversalDepth {\\n   109→       // ...\\n   110→       if i == MaxCommitTraversalDepth-1 && len(commit.ParentHashes) > 0 {\\n   111→           return nil, fmt.Errorf(\\\"commit chain exceeded %d commits; aborting reconciliation\\\", MaxCommitTraversalDepth)\\n   112→       }\\n   113→   }\\n   114→   ```\\n   115→\\n   116→6. **[common.go:55-59] `EnsureMetadataReconciled` captures the first `repo` parameter forever**\\n   117→\\n   118→   The `sync.Once` closure captures whichever `*git.Repository` is passed on the first call. If the function is called first from one code path with repo A, then from another with repo B, repo B's call will get repo A's result -- which may or may not apply. In this codebase, the `*git.Repository` is typically re-opened for each operation, so two different `repo` objects could point to the same underlying repo. This is *probably* fine since the reconciliation is a ref-level operation that's visible to all `*git.Repository` instances for the same repo. But the API is misleading -- it accepts a `repo` parameter that is silently ignored on all calls after the first.\\n   119→\\n   120→   **Suggested fix:** Consider documenting this behavior or, better, removing the `repo` parameter and having `EnsureMetadataReconciled` open its own repo internally (matching how `ListCheckpoints` opens its own repo):\\n   121→   ```go\\n   122→   func EnsureMetadataReconciled() error {\\n   123→       reconcileOnce.Do(func() {\\n   124→           repo, err := OpenRepository(context.Background())\\n   125→           if err != nil {\\n   126→               reconcileResult = err\\n   127→               return\\n   128→           }\\n   129→           reconcileResult = ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch(repo)\\n   130→       })\\n   131→       return reconcileResult\\n   132→   }\\n   133→   ```\\n   134→   This would also simplify the callers.\\n   135→\\n   136→### Suggestions (Consider)\\n   137→\\n   138→7. **[metadata_reconcile.go:73, 99, 103, 116] User-facing messages go to stderr without structured logging**\\n   139→\\n   140→   The reconciliation messages use `fmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr, ...)` directly, while the project guidelines say operational messages should use the `logging` package. These messages are user-facing status updates about a repair operation, so `os.Stderr` is arguably appropriate, but the inconsistency with the `logging.Warn` usage in `explain.go:890` stands out. Consider whether these should also use `logging.Info` or `logging.Warn` with a context.\\n   141→\\n   142→8. **[metadata_reconcile.go:128-141] `isDisconnected` creates its own `context.Background()` instead of accepting a context**\\n   143→\\n   144→   The function creates a 10-second timeout context internally. If the caller already has a context (e.g., with a shorter deadline or cancellation), this is not respected. Consider threading the caller's context through:\\n   145→   ```go\\n   146→   func isDisconnected(ctx context.Context, repoPath, hashA, hashB string) (bool, error) {\\n   147→       ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(ctx, 10*time.Second)\\n   148→       defer cancel()\\n   149→       // ...\\n   150→   }\\n   151→   ```\\n   152→   The same applies to `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch` -- it could accept a `context.Context` parameter.\\n   153→\\n   154→9. **[metadata_reconcile.go:258-285] `createCherryPickCommit` calls `GetGitAuthorFromRepo` for each commit**\\n   155→\\n   156→   When cherry-picking N commits, `GetGitAuthorFromRepo` is called N times. It reads the git config each time. Consider computing the author once and passing it in, or accepting it as a parameter.\\n   157→\\n   158→10. **[common.go:336-341] Comment says \\\"reconciliation is handled by EnsureMetadataReconciled at read/write time\\\" but no further action taken**\\n   159→\\n   160→    When `EnsureMetadataBranch` detects a non-empty local branch that differs from remote and is NOT empty, it silently returns nil. The comment correctly notes reconciliation happens elsewhere, but there is no warning or logging that a disconnected state was detected (the user only sees the fix later, if/when `EnsureMetadataReconciled` runs). Consider adding a debug log here so the `entire enable` output gives some indication.\\n   161→\\n   162→11. **[metadata_reconcile.go:288-294] `getRepoPath` uses `repo.Worktree()` which fails for bare repos**\\n   163→\\n   164→    This function will panic or error on bare repos. While the CLI normally operates on non-bare repos, `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch` is a public function and could be called in other contexts. Consider adding a comment about this limitation or a guard.\\n   165→\\n   166→12. **[metadata_reconcile_test.go] No test for the `collectCommitChain` depth limit or for repos where `isDisconnected` returns an error from git**\\n   167→\\n   168→    The test suite thoroughly covers the happy paths and main scenarios. Consider adding:\\n   169→    - A test for when `git merge-base` is not available (e.g., PATH is broken)\\n   170→    - A test that the empty-tree commit created by the orphan bug is correctly identified and filtered (currently tested implicitly via `TestReconcileDisconnected_MultipleLocalCheckpoints` but a targeted unit test for the filtering logic would be clearer)\\n   171→\\n   172→### Praise\\n   173→\\n   174→- **Clean separation of concerns**: Moving reconciliation out of `EnsureMetadataBranch` (called at `enable` time, sometimes offline) into `EnsureMetadataReconciled` (called at read/write time when remote refs are available) is a well-thought-out design change. The old location would fail for users who run `entire enable` before fetching.\\n   175→\\n   176→- **Thorough test coverage**: Six tests covering no-remote, no-local, same-hash, shared-ancestry, disconnected, and multiple-checkpoints scenarios is excellent coverage for the core reconciliation logic. The `TestReconcileDisconnected_ModifiedEntries` test specifically targeting delta correctness (not just additions) shows good attention to detail.\\n   177→\\n   178→- **Correct delta computation**: The `cherryPickOnto` function properly computes additions, modifications, AND deletions by diffing each commit against its parent rather than just using the commit's tree directly. This handles the multi-session condensation case where a checkpoint's metadata.json is updated in place.\\n   179→\\n   180→- **Defensive early returns**: The main `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch` function has clear guard clauses for no-local, no-remote, same-hash, and shared-ancestry cases before attempting any repair.\\n   181→\\n   182→- **Good use of existing checkpoint utilities**: Reusing `checkpoint.FlattenTree` and `checkpoint.BuildTreeFromEntries` avoids code duplication.\\n   183→\\n   184→## Summary\\n   185→\\n   186→- **Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES**\\n   187→- **Key concerns:**\\n   188→  - The test file has a fragile error-as-control-flow pattern that should be a simple mkdir+write (item 1)\\n   189→  - The `sync.Once` global lacks a test reset mechanism, creating a latent test isolation issue (item 2)\\n   190→  - Silent error swallowing in `FlattenTree` parent processing (item 4) could produce incorrect cherry-picks in edge cases\\n   191→  - The `repo` parameter to `EnsureMetadataReconciled` is misleading since it's captured only on first call (item 6)\\n   192→- **Estimated effort to address feedback:** 1-2 hours for Critical + Important items\\n   193→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"606b80d3-f5e0-46ed-9818-7ac1f5cc3818\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-26T23:42:35.452Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"type\":\"text\",\"file\":{\"filePath\":\"/Users/dvydra/src/cli/docs/requirements/reconcile-disconnected-metadata/review-01.md\",\"content\":\"# Review 01\\n\\n> Status: pending-dev\\n> Date: 2026-02-27\\n> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n> Verdict: REQUEST CHANGES\\n\\n## Previous Review Status\\nN/A - first review\\n\\n## New Findings\\n\\n### Critical (Must Fix)\\n\\n1. **[metadata_reconcile_test.go:405-414] Fragile file-creation logic uses error as control flow**\\n\\n   The test attempts to write a file into a directory that does not yet exist, then catches the error to create the directory, then retries the write. This is fragile and confusing -- if the write fails for any other reason (e.g., disk full, permissions), the test would silently create the directory and retry instead of failing.\\n\\n   ```go\\n   if err := os.WriteFile(filepath.Join(dir1, \\\"1\\\", \\\"metadata.json\\\"),\\n       []byte(`{\\\"session_id\\\":\\\"second-session\\\"}`), 0o644); err != nil {\\n       if err := os.MkdirAll(filepath.Join(dir1, \\\"1\\\"), 0o755); err != nil {\\n           t.Fatalf(\\\"failed to create dir: %v\\\", err)\\n       }\\n       if err := os.WriteFile(filepath.Join(dir1, \\\"1\\\", \\\"metadata.json\\\"),\\n           []byte(`{\\\"session_id\\\":\\\"second-session\\\"}`), 0o644); err != nil {\\n           t.Fatalf(\\\"failed to write: %v\\\", err)\\n       }\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n   **Suggested fix:** Create the directory first unconditionally, then write the file:\\n   ```go\\n   if err := os.MkdirAll(filepath.Join(dir1, \\\"1\\\"), 0o755); err != nil {\\n       t.Fatalf(\\\"failed to create dir: %v\\\", err)\\n   }\\n   if err := os.WriteFile(filepath.Join(dir1, \\\"1\\\", \\\"metadata.json\\\"),\\n       []byte(`{\\\"session_id\\\":\\\"second-session\\\"}`), 0o644); err != nil {\\n       t.Fatalf(\\\"failed to write: %v\\\", err)\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n2. **[common.go:48-59] `sync.Once` global state is not resettable for testing**\\n\\n   The `reconcileOnce` / `reconcileResult` globals use `sync.Once` which means reconciliation runs exactly once per process. This is correct for production, but it creates implicit test ordering dependencies. If any test (or future test) calls `EnsureMetadataReconciled`, the cached result will persist for all subsequent tests in the same `go test` process.\\n\\n   Currently no tests call `EnsureMetadataReconciled` directly, and the reconcile tests call `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch` directly (which is good). But the `getCheckpointStore()` method in `manual_commit.go:55` calls `EnsureMetadataReconciled`, and `ListCheckpoints` in `common.go:135` also calls it. If any integration test triggers these paths, a stale cached error (or a stale nil from a test repo) will leak.\\n\\n   The pattern used elsewhere in this codebase (e.g., `resetProtectedDirsForTest` in `common_test.go:851-854`) is to provide a test-only reset function.\\n\\n   **Suggested fix:** Add a reset function for tests:\\n   ```go\\n   // resetReconcileOnceForTest resets the reconciliation gate for test isolation.\\n   //\\n   //nolint:unused // test utility\\n   func resetReconcileOnceForTest() {\\n       reconcileOnce = sync.Once{}\\n       reconcileResult = nil\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n   This is not yet causing failures, but it is a latent correctness issue.\\n\\n### Important (Should Fix)\\n\\n3. **[metadata_reconcile.go:83-91] Silent `continue` on tree error swallows potential real errors**\\n\\n   When filtering empty-tree commits, the code silently skips any commit where `c.Tree()` fails:\\n   ```go\\n   tree, treeErr := c.Tree()\\n   if treeErr != nil {\\n       continue\\n   }\\n   ```\\n   If the tree object is genuinely corrupted or missing (as opposed to empty), this silently drops a data commit. This should at least log a warning. In the normal case (the empty-orphan bug), `c.Tree()` will succeed and return an empty tree -- there is no reason for `Tree()` to fail on a valid commit.\\n\\n   **Suggested fix:** Return an error or at minimum log a warning when `Tree()` fails on a commit that does exist:\\n   ```go\\n   tree, treeErr := c.Tree()\\n   if treeErr != nil {\\n       fmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \\\"[entire] Warning: skipping commit %s with unreadable tree: %v\\\\n\\\", c.Hash.String()[:7], treeErr)\\n       continue\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n4. **[metadata_reconcile.go:194] Best-effort `FlattenTree` on parent silently ignores errors**\\n\\n   ```go\\n   _ = checkpoint.FlattenTree(repo, parentTree, \\\"\\\", parentEntries) //nolint:errcheck // best effort\\n   ```\\n   If `FlattenTree` fails on the parent tree, `parentEntries` will be partially populated. The delta computation will then treat any entries that were *not* read as \\\"deleted\\\" in the parent, and any entries that *were* in the commit will be treated as \\\"new.\\\" This could result in an incomplete or incorrect delta being cherry-picked. Since this is a repair operation for user data, correctness should take priority over resilience.\\n\\n   **Suggested fix:** Propagate the error:\\n   ```go\\n   if err := checkpoint.FlattenTree(repo, parentTree, \\\"\\\", parentEntries); err != nil {\\n       return plumbing.ZeroHash, fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to flatten parent tree for commit %s: %w\\\", commit.Hash, err)\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n5. **[metadata_reconcile.go:144-167] `collectCommitChain` silently stops at MaxCommitTraversalDepth without warning**\\n\\n   If the local metadata branch has more than 1000 commits (unlikely but possible for heavy users), `collectCommitChain` silently truncates the chain. The cherry-pick would then only replay the most recent 1000 commits, losing older data.\\n\\n   The `for range MaxCommitTraversalDepth` loop exits silently when the limit is reached without reaching the root commit. The caller has no way to know data was truncated.\\n\\n   **Suggested fix:** Either return an error when the depth limit is hit without reaching a root commit, or log a warning:\\n   ```go\\n   for i := range MaxCommitTraversalDepth {\\n       // ...\\n       if i == MaxCommitTraversalDepth-1 && len(commit.ParentHashes) > 0 {\\n           return nil, fmt.Errorf(\\\"commit chain exceeded %d commits; aborting reconciliation\\\", MaxCommitTraversalDepth)\\n       }\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n6. **[common.go:55-59] `EnsureMetadataReconciled` captures the first `repo` parameter forever**\\n\\n   The `sync.Once` closure captures whichever `*git.Repository` is passed on the first call. If the function is called first from one code path with repo A, then from another with repo B, repo B's call will get repo A's result -- which may or may not apply. In this codebase, the `*git.Repository` is typically re-opened for each operation, so two different `repo` objects could point to the same underlying repo. This is *probably* fine since the reconciliation is a ref-level operation that's visible to all `*git.Repository` instances for the same repo. But the API is misleading -- it accepts a `repo` parameter that is silently ignored on all calls after the first.\\n\\n   **Suggested fix:** Consider documenting this behavior or, better, removing the `repo` parameter and having `EnsureMetadataReconciled` open its own repo internally (matching how `ListCheckpoints` opens its own repo):\\n   ```go\\n   func EnsureMetadataReconciled() error {\\n       reconcileOnce.Do(func() {\\n           repo, err := OpenRepository(context.Background())\\n           if err != nil {\\n               reconcileResult = err\\n               return\\n           }\\n           reconcileResult = ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch(repo)\\n       })\\n       return reconcileResult\\n   }\\n   ```\\n   This would also simplify the callers.\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n7. **[metadata_reconcile.go:73, 99, 103, 116] User-facing messages go to stderr without structured logging**\\n\\n   The reconciliation messages use `fmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr, ...)` directly, while the project guidelines say operational messages should use the `logging` package. These messages are user-facing status updates about a repair operation, so `os.Stderr` is arguably appropriate, but the inconsistency with the `logging.Warn` usage in `explain.go:890` stands out. Consider whether these should also use `logging.Info` or `logging.Warn` with a context.\\n\\n8. **[metadata_reconcile.go:128-141] `isDisconnected` creates its own `context.Background()` instead of accepting a context**\\n\\n   The function creates a 10-second timeout context internally. If the caller already has a context (e.g., with a shorter deadline or cancellation), this is not respected. Consider threading the caller's context through:\\n   ```go\\n   func isDisconnected(ctx context.Context, repoPath, hashA, hashB string) (bool, error) {\\n       ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(ctx, 10*time.Second)\\n       defer cancel()\\n       // ...\\n   }\\n   ```\\n   The same applies to `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch` -- it could accept a `context.Context` parameter.\\n\\n9. **[metadata_reconcile.go:258-285] `createCherryPickCommit` calls `GetGitAuthorFromRepo` for each commit**\\n\\n   When cherry-picking N commits, `GetGitAuthorFromRepo` is called N times. It reads the git config each time. Consider computing the author once and passing it in, or accepting it as a parameter.\\n\\n10. **[common.go:336-341] Comment says \\\"reconciliation is handled by EnsureMetadataReconciled at read/write time\\\" but no further action taken**\\n\\n    When `EnsureMetadataBranch` detects a non-empty local branch that differs from remote and is NOT empty, it silently returns nil. The comment correctly notes reconciliation happens elsewhere, but there is no warning or logging that a disconnected state was detected (the user only sees the fix later, if/when `EnsureMetadataReconciled` runs). Consider adding a debug log here so the `entire enable` output gives some indication.\\n\\n11. **[metadata_reconcile.go:288-294] `getRepoPath` uses `repo.Worktree()` which fails for bare repos**\\n\\n    This function will panic or error on bare repos. While the CLI normally operates on non-bare repos, `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch` is a public function and could be called in other contexts. Consider adding a comment about this limitation or a guard.\\n\\n12. **[metadata_reconcile_test.go] No test for the `collectCommitChain` depth limit or for repos where `isDisconnected` returns an error from git**\\n\\n    The test suite thoroughly covers the happy paths and main scenarios. Consider adding:\\n    - A test for when `git merge-base` is not available (e.g., PATH is broken)\\n    - A test that the empty-tree commit created by the orphan bug is correctly identified and filtered (currently tested implicitly via `TestReconcileDisconnected_MultipleLocalCheckpoints` but a targeted unit test for the filtering logic would be clearer)\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n- **Clean separation of concerns**: Moving reconciliation out of `EnsureMetadataBranch` (called at `enable` time, sometimes offline) into `EnsureMetadataReconciled` (called at read/write time when remote refs are available) is a well-thought-out design change. The old location would fail for users who run `entire enable` before fetching.\\n\\n- **Thorough test coverage**: Six tests covering no-remote, no-local, same-hash, shared-ancestry, disconnected, and multiple-checkpoints scenarios is excellent coverage for the core reconciliation logic. The `TestReconcileDisconnected_ModifiedEntries` test specifically targeting delta correctness (not just additions) shows good attention to detail.\\n\\n- **Correct delta computation**: The `cherryPickOnto` function properly computes additions, modifications, AND deletions by diffing each commit against its parent rather than just using the commit's tree directly. This handles the multi-session condensation case where a checkpoint's metadata.json is updated in place.\\n\\n- **Defensive early returns**: The main `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch` function has clear guard clauses for no-local, no-remote, same-hash, and shared-ancestry cases before attempting any repair.\\n\\n- **Good use of existing checkpoint utilities**: Reusing `checkpoint.FlattenTree` and `checkpoint.BuildTreeFromEntries` avoids code duplication.\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n- **Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES**\\n- **Key concerns:**\\n  - The test file has a fragile error-as-control-flow pattern that should be a simple mkdir+write (item 1)\\n  - The `sync.Once` global lacks a test reset mechanism, creating a latent test isolation issue (item 2)\\n  - Silent error swallowing in `FlattenTree` parent processing (item 4) could produce incorrect cherry-picks in edge cases\\n  - The `repo` parameter to `EnsureMetadataReconciled` is misleading since it's captured only on first call (item 6)\\n- **Estimated effort to address feedback:** 1-2 hours for Critical + Important items\\n\",\"numLines\":193,\"startLine\":1,\"totalLines\":193}},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"a3b240bf-fbfa-4621-a484-e86aa4cafa9b\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"606b80d3-f5e0-46ed-9818-7ac1f5cc3818\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/dvydra/src/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"42e0519f-9103-4bac-8c5e-804338fd82f2\",\"version\":\"2.1.59\",\"gitBranch\":\"fix/reconcile-disconnected-metadata-branch\",\"slug\":\"tranquil-launching-duckling\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01NysKSzEqXMbkyeU517VeBM\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Here's the full review:\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Review: REQUEST CHANGES\\n\\n### Critical (2)\\n\\n**1. [metadata_reconcile_test.go:405-414] Fragile file-creation logic uses error as control flow**\\n\\nThe test tries to write a file, catches the error to create the directory, then retries. Should just be `os.MkdirAll` then `os.WriteFile`.\\n\\n**2. [common.go:48-59] `sync.Once` global state is not resettable for testing**\\n\\nNo `resetReconcileOnceForTest()` function exists (unlike `resetProtectedDirsForTest`). If any integration test triggers `EnsureMetadataReconciled` via `getCheckpointStore()` or `ListCheckpoints`, a stale cached result will leak to subsequent tests.\\n\\n### Important (4)\\n\\n**3. [metadata_reconcile.go:83-91] Silent `continue` on tree error swallows real errors**\\n\\nWhen filtering empty-tree commits, `c.Tree()` errors are silently skipped. A corrupted tree would cause a data commit to be silently dropped during repair. Should at least log a warning.\\n\\n**4. [metadata_reconcile.go:194] Best-effort `FlattenTree` on parent silently ignores errors**\\n\\nIf `FlattenTree` fails partially, `parentEntries` is incomplete. The delta computation then treats unread entries as \\\"deleted\\\" and produces an incorrect cherry-pick. Since this is a data repair operation, the error should propagate.\\n\\n**5. [metadata_reconcile.go:144-167] `collectCommitChain` silently stops at MaxCommitTraversalDepth**\\n\\nIf local metadata branch has >1000 commits, chain is silently truncated — older data is lost without warning. Should return an error when the limit is hit without reaching a root commit.\\n\\n**6. [common.go:55-59] `EnsureMetadataReconciled` captures first `repo` forever**\\n\\nThe `repo` parameter is only used on the first call. Subsequent calls with different repos silently ignore the parameter. Consider removing the parameter and having it open its own repo internally (like `ListCheckpoints` does).\\n\\n### Suggestions (6)\\n\\n**7.** Reconciliation messages use `fmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr)` directly while project guidelines prefer the `logging` package for operational messages.\\n\\n**8.** `isDisconnected` creates its own `context.Background()` instead of accepting a caller context.\\n\\n**9.** `createCherryPickCommit` calls `GetGitAuthorFromRepo` per commit instead of computing once.\\n\\n**10.** `EnsureMetadataBranch` silently returns nil when it detects a non-empty diverged state — no logging that disconnected state was noticed.\\n\\n**11.** `getRepoPath` uses `repo.Worktree()` which fails for bare repos. `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch` is public.\\n\\n**12.** No test for `collectCommitChain` depth limit or for when `git merge-base` is unavailable.\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n- Clean separation of concerns moving reconciliation from enable-time to read/write-time\\n- Thorough test coverage (7 scenarios including modification delta)\\n- Correct full delta computation (adds + modifies + deletes)\\n- Defensive early returns in the main function\\n- Good reuse of existing `checkpoint.FlattenTree` / `BuildTreeFromEntries`\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":4175,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":145273,\"output_tokens\":817,\"server_tool_use\":{\"web_search_requests\":0,\"web_fetch_requests\":0},\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":4175,\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0},\"inference_geo\":\"\",\"iterations\":[],\"speed\":\"standard\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYXZqMaWk1Ub7m9V7QGk8\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"3a34022a-f0c6-4519-b73a-d72db6822031\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-26T23:42:49.515Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"3a34022a-f0c6-4519-b73a-d72db6822031\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/dvydra/src/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"42e0519f-9103-4bac-8c5e-804338fd82f2\",\"version\":\"2.1.59\",\"gitBranch\":\"fix/reconcile-disconnected-metadata-branch\",\"slug\":\"tranquil-launching-duckling\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"Stop\",\"hookName\":\"Stop\",\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code stop\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"dc8d20a4-3dfa-4a95-8b3c-31ddbc7cace8\",\"toolUseID\":\"dc8d20a4-3dfa-4a95-8b3c-31ddbc7cace8\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-26T23:42:49.548Z\",\"uuid\":\"fef7829a-1c0c-4e77-ac25-cb7c2ef146b2\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"fef7829a-1c0c-4e77-ac25-cb7c2ef146b2\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/dvydra/src/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"42e0519f-9103-4bac-8c5e-804338fd82f2\",\"version\":\"2.1.59\",\"gitBranch\":\"fix/reconcile-disconnected-metadata-branch\",\"slug\":\"tranquil-launching-duckling\",\"type\":\"system\",\"subtype\":\"stop_hook_summary\",\"hookCount\":1,\"hookInfos\":[{\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJEC